\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f1\fs18\b0\i0\super\cf1 10\~}{\f1\fs18\b0\i0\cf1 Cases decided by the Courts of Appeals since the enactment of the 1972 amendments to Title VII similarly provide us with little guidance as to the scope of the employer's obligation.  In circumstances where an employer has declined to take steps that would burden some employees in order to permit another employee or prospective employee to observe his Sabbath, the Fifth, Sixth, and Tenth Circuits have found no violation for failure to accommodate. ; , cert. denied, }{\f2\fs18\b0\i1\cf1 429 U.S. 964 (1976)}{\f1\fs18\b0\i0\cf1 , pet. for rehearing pending, No. 75-1105; . But the Fifth and Sixth Circuits have also reached the opposite conclusion on similar facts.  ; , aff'd by equally divided ; . These apparent intra-Circuit conflicts may be explainable on the basis of the differing facts of each case, but neither the Fifth nor the Sixth Circuit has suggested a theory of decision to justify the differing results that have been reached.}}]]></Comment>
